## Woops

Well that didn't work. What went wrong?
After deliberating with my professor, he gave me some insight into what may have gone wrong.
The feature space is just very large for the neural net to learn. 32x32x32x200 is large and explodes quickly.
The model needs to learn this space and characterize it to predict make decent predictions, without unreasonable
compute and a million or more datapoints, this would be completely impossible.

To solve this, we need some sort of dimension reduction. Specifically, one that is trainable.

Enter Variational Auto Encoders.

---

## Variational Auto Encoders

These models take input data and find a mapping to and from arbitrary probability distributions. 
In this case, we map from a 32x32x32x256 space, to some 100-dimensional multivariate gaussian latent space.
These mappings are obviously non-trivial. The complexity is handled by CNN's to encode and decode the latent space.

Then we can take this 100-dimensional latent vector and run diffusion on it, map it back into data, and see an output.

This is known as latent diffusion and has had great success in practice.

